comments.body: I am a herpetologist but I have certainly goofed on some IDs outside of my realm of expertise here on iNat so it happens to all of us.  That is the beauty of this community though...there are verified experts and nature lovers and school kids and everyone in between all sharing their observations and the collective minds/knowledge of all these individuals come together in consensus for positive IDs. We all have room to grow and learn!

Well I wasn't the only one there, my brother is pretty knowledgeable with snakes , as is my Brother Inlaw, everyone thought it was a Rattle Snake, but I guess maybe we stand corrected, though I still have my doubts.

@cmcheatle and @ritt  thank you for taking the time to write your additional comments. @kittyandpaulmartin I hope that you will understand that no one is judging you here and you should not feel threatened to have experts assist you in identifying their observation.  As others have mentioned many species of non-venomous snakes will vibrate their tails in an attempt to warn off potential predators. Also while pupil shape isn't the best character to use to distinguish between venomous and non-venomous snakes since it can change shape dramatically due to lighting.  For this snake the shape of the head, the scale pattern on the head, the pattern on the body and several other characters all point to this being a Fox snake not a Massauga.

UPDATE - Obviously I was writing this as the above comment was being submitted, I did not mean to be perceived as piling on, or anything like that.

I don't want to discourage you from participating, the community here is trying to be helpful. I'm from 50 kilometers north of there (grew up in Pointe au Baril), so know the area and its snakes just like you. Please look closely at the picture #3 in particular, you can see the snakes has large round pupils. All venomous snakes in North America with the exception of Coral Snakes have thin "slit" pupils.

You can see examples here :
https://mnfi.anr.msu.edu/emr/id.cfm
http://www.massasauga.ca/html/stewardship/section3.pdf
http://www.ojibway.ca/rattler.htm - this article even describes how when threatened the Foxsnake often imitates rattlesnakes by shaking their tail.

Tail rattling is a very common defensive behavior in a wide variety of snakes (e.g. rat snakes, racers, milk snakes, king snakes, fox snakes, among others), and is not unique to rattlesnakes. Among dry leaf litter, this can produce a sound similar to a rattlesnake. Head shape, pupil shape, and coloration all indicate this is a Foxsnake rather than a Massassauga.
you're wrong, it was a rattle snake, it was rattling, and we saw the tail, I just wasn't going to get to close to get a detailed pic.
Plus the pupil is round, which is only seen in 1 North American venomous snake (Massassauga would have a slit pupil)
Look at the head in the 4th picture. Wrong shape to be a Sisturus.

results.description:
I haven't seen one of these in years, so this was an awesome find in the beaver pond near our families cottage. This isn't an Eastern Fox Snake, it was rattling , we saw it's rattle, so it's not a hog nose, it is a rattle snake, it was on Huckle Berry Island , on Parry Sound, in Georgian Bay, it's known for rattle snakes on the islands.
https://barrie.ctvnews.ca/increase-of-rattlesnake-bites-near-georgian-bay-a-growing-concern-1.2493736 

This is an article describing the snakes, I've seen rattle snakes before so I know what it was.
